{"title_page": "John Macreadie", "text_new": "'''John Macreadie''' (19 September 1946 \u2013 22 December 2010) was a Scottish trade unionist and a longstanding supporter of [[Militant (Trotskyist group)|Militant]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in Glasgow, he left the city in his teens in the 60's to take up a job at the [[Department for Transport|Ministry of Transport]] in London,<ref>\n{{cite news |first=Carolyn |last=Churchill |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/tributes-to-class-fighter-for-union-1.1076532 |title=Tributes to \u2018class fighter\u2019 for union |newspaper=Herald Scotland |date=27 December 2010 |accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> where he was also active within the [[Acton, London|Acton]] Young Socialists.<ref name=\"SPobit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.socialistparty.org.uk/articles/10842/22-12-2010/tribute-to-john-macreadie |title=Tribute to John Macreadie |date=22 December 2010 |publisher=Socialist Party |work=Socialist Party website |accessdate=31 December 2010 }}</ref> He joined the [[Civil and Public Services Association]] and was appointed to a full-time post within the union in 1970.<ref name=\"SPobit\"/> In 1977 he led the successful [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]] Air Traffic Control Assistants strike.<ref name=\"SPobit\"/>\n\n==1986 General Secretary Election Controversy==\n\nIn 1986, Macreadie stood for the post of [[General Secretary]] of the CPSA. In the elections, Macreadie initially won the ballot. However, the election was blocked and the courts ordered it to be re-run, with John Ellis receiving 42,000 votes, Macreadie receiving 31,000, and the Broad Left 84, backed by the [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist Party]] gaining 13,000.<ref>{{cite book |last=Taaffe |first=Peter |date=November 30, 1995 |title=Rise of \"Militant\": Thirty Years of \"Militant\" | publisher=Militant Publications|pages=292\u20133 |isbn=978-0-906582-47-3}}</ref>\n\nMacreadie was later elected as Deputy General Secretary of the union in 1987 and was named as one of a 'dirty half-dozen' by Ellis in an expos\u00e9 of the Militant-led left in the union.<ref>Article from [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] referenced in: {{cite web |last=Black |first=C. |title=Autumn 87: How Lefties Make My Union Job A Nightmare |date=15 September 1987 |url=http://www.pflcpsa.com/aut_87.htm |accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> Macreadie also served on the [[General Council of the TUC]] from 1987 to 1988.<ref>[TUC General Council report 2011 {{cite web|url=http://www.tuc.org.uk/extras/GCreport2011.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120907052706/http://www.tuc.org.uk/extras/GCreport2011.pdf |archivedate=2012-09-07 }}] - retrieved 24/2/2012</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n\nAfter being unsuccessful in further senior union official elections, Macreadie continued as a national CPSA, then [[Public and Commercial Services Union|PCS]] officer, eventually taking up a position as advisor to [[Mark Serwotka]] when he was elected as General Secretary in 2002.<ref name=\"SPobit\"/> He retired from the PCS in 2005<ref name=\"SPobit\"/> and died of a brain tumour in France in December 2010, aged 64.<ref>{{cite web | first=Janice| last=Godrich| authorlink=Janice Godrich| url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jan/17/john-macreadie-obituary| title=John Macreadie obituary| publisher=[[The Guardian]]| date=17 January 2011| accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jan/17/john-macreadie-obituary John Macreadie obituary | From the Guardian | The Guardian ]\n* [http://www.socialistparty.org.uk/articles/10876 Obituary from the Socialist]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macreadie, John}}\n[[Category:Scottish Trotskyists]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Militant tendency supporters]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party (England and Wales) members]]\n[[Category:Scottish trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Members of the General Council of the Trades Union Congress]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Macreadie''' (19 September 1946 \u2013 22 December 2010) was a Scottish trade unionist and a longstanding supporter of [[Militant (Trotskyist group)|Militant]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in Glasgow, he left the city in his teens in the 60's to take up a job at the [[Department for Transport|Ministry of Transport]] in London,<ref>\n{{cite news |first=Carolyn |last=Churchill |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/tributes-to-class-fighter-for-union-1.1076532 |title=Tributes to \u2018class fighter\u2019 for union |newspaper=Herald Scotland |date=27 December 2010 |accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> where he was also active within the [[Acton, London|Acton]] Young Socialists.<ref name=\"SPobit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.socialistparty.org.uk/articles/10842/22-12-2010/tribute-to-john-macreadie |title=Tribute to John Macreadie |date=22 December 2010 |publisher=Socialist Party |work=Socialist Party website |accessdate=31 December 2010 }}</ref> He joined the [[Civil and Public Services Association]] and was appointed to a full-time post within the union in 1970.<ref name=\"SPobit\"/> In 1977 he led the successful [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]] Air Traffic Control Assistants strike.<ref name=\"SPobit\"/>\n\n==1986 General Secretary Election Controversy==\n\nIn 1986, Macreadie stood for the post of [[General Secretary]] of the CPSA. In the elections, Macreadie initially won the ballot. However, the election was blocked and the courts ordered it to be re-run, with John Ellis receiving 42,000 votes, Macreadie receiving 31,000, and the Broad Left 84, backed by the [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist Party]] gaining 13,000.<ref>{{cite book |last=Taaffe |first=Peter |date=November 30, 1995 |title=Rise of \"Militant\": Thirty Years of \"Militant\" | publisher=Militant Publications|pages=292\u20133 |isbn=978-0-906582-47-3}}</ref>\n\nMacreadie was later elected as Deputy General Secretary of the union in 1987 and was named as one of a 'dirty half-dozen' by Ellis in an expos\u00e9 of the Militant-led left in the union.<ref>Article from [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] referenced in: {{cite web |last=Black |first=C. |title=Autumn 87: How Lefties Make My Union Job A Nightmare |date=15 September 1987 |url=http://www.pflcpsa.com/aut_87.htm |accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> Macreadie also served on the [[General Council of the TUC]] from 1987 to 1988.<ref>[TUC General Council report 2011 {{cite web|url=http://www.tuc.org.uk/extras/GCreport2011.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120907052706/http://www.tuc.org.uk/extras/GCreport2011.pdf |archivedate=2012-09-07 }}] - retrieved 24/2/2012</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n\nAfter being unsuccessful in further senior union official elections, Macreadie continued as a national CPSA, then [[Public and Commercial Services Union|PCS]] officer, eventually taking up a position as advisor to [[Mark Serwotka]] when he was elected as General Secretary in 2002.<ref name=\"SPobit\"/> He retired from the PCS in 2005<ref name=\"SPobit\"/> and died of a brain tumour in France in December 2010, aged 64.<ref>{{cite web | first=Janice| last=Godrich| authorlink=Janice Godrich| url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jan/17/john-macreadie-obituary| title=John Macreadie obituary| publisher=[[The Guardian]]| date=17 January 2011| accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jan/17/john-macreadie-obituary John Macreadie obituary | From the Guardian | The Guardian ]\n* [http://www.socialistparty.org.uk/articles/10876 Obituary from the Socialist]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macreadie, John}}\n[[Category:Scottish Trotskyists]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\